<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-12-22T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-12-22T22:00:00-05:00" n="150" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d150">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/1722</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Reinsch</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-12-23T11:00:00+08:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 23, 1916, 11 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your statement of the position of the American Government in the matter
                            of loans was received in a friendly manner by the representatives <pb facs="0226" n="150" xml:id="pg_150"/> concerned who stated no
                            objection to Chicago loan, but all expressed a desire for American
                            cooperation in reorganization loan. Full report by mail.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>